[[File:Japanese Primordial Deities-ja.svg|thumb|right|200px|天地開闢 [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b5/Japanese Primordial Deities-ja.svg View as SVG]]]
'''Uhijini''' (宇比地邇, also rendered as '''Nidotsuchi''') and '''Suhijini''' (須比智邇, also rendered as '''Satotsuchi''') are deities in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話}}.
## Overview In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}, Uhijini no Kami is the elder brother, and Suhijini no Kami is the younger sister. The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} names them Nidotsuchi no Mikoto and Satotsuchi no Mikoto. In the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀}}, their names are given as Mud-Ground Deity and Sand-Ground Deity.
They are considered the third generation of {{ill|Kamiyo Nanayo|ja|神世七代}}. These are the first paired male and female deities in the creation myths of Japan, succeeding the independent deities of prior generations.
### Significance of Names "Uhi" refers to mud (from the ancient term "uki"), while "Suhi" refers to sand. Together, their names describe the formation of the earth's surface through layers of mud and sand.
- **Uhijini**: "Uhi" (mud) + "Jini" (ground deity) symbolizes the primordial mud consolidating into solid ground. - **Suhijini**: "Suhi" (sand) + "Jini" (ground deity) represents the blending of sand with earth, completing the groundwork for life.
### Phonetic Notes In the original Kojiki text, phonetic notes indicate that the "Jini" in Uhijini is pronounced with a rising intonation, while the "Jini" in Suhijini is pronounced with a falling intonation.
