'''Uhijini''' (宇比地邇, also pronounced '''Uhijini''') and '''Suhijini''' (須比智邇, also known as '''Suhichini''') are deities in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==

In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}, Uhijini no Kami is described as the elder brother, while Suhijini no Kami is his younger sister. The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}} refers to them as Nidotsuchi no Mikoto and Satotsuchi no Mikoto, respectively. The {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft}} uses Nidotsune no Mikoto and Satotsune no Mikoto.

They are the third pair of deities in the {{ill|Kamiyonanayo|ja|神世七代|1=Kamiyonanayo|2=ja|3=神世七代|12=draft}} lineage and the first male-female pairing after generations of {{ill|Hitorigami|ja|独神|12=draft}}. 

The names signify the formation of land as mud and sand start to shape it. Uhijini no Kami’s name translates to "the first mud," while Suhijini no Kami signifies "sand and mud." These deities symbolize the earth solidifying and forming recognizable features. Their names indicate affection with the suffix "-ni" expressing endearment.

